V'''Henry Babcock Veatch, Jr.''' (September 26, 1911 &ndash; July 9, 1999) was an American [[philosopher]].\u000a\u000a==Life and career==\u000aVeatch was born in [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]], [[Indiana]].  He obtained his [[Ph.D.]] from [[Harvard University]] in 1937 and spent his career at [[Indiana University]] (1937&ndash;1965), [[Northwestern University]] (1965&ndash;1973), and [[Georgetown University]] (1973&ndash;1983) where he was Philosophy Department Chair from 1973 to 1976.  He also had visiting professorships at [[Colby College]], [[Haverford College]] and [[St. Thomas University (New Brunswick)|St. Thomas University]].\u000a\u000aVeatch was active in the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] and served as president of the [http://www.acpaweb.org/ American Catholic Philosophical Association]. He served as president of the [[Metaphysical Society of America]] in 1961. In 1970&ndash;71 he served as president of the Western Division of the [[American Philosophical Association]]. He was a member of the [[Guild of Scholars of The Episcopal Church]].\u000a\u000aHenry Veatch died in [[Bloomington (Indiana)|Bloomington]], [[Indiana]].  Indiana University maintains the [http://purl.dlib.indiana.edu/iudl/findingaids/archives/InU-Ar-VAA2654 archive of his collected papers (1941&ndash;1997)].\u000a\u000a==Philosophy==\u000aVeatch was a major proponent of [[rationalism]], an authority on [[Thomism|Thomistic philosophy]], and one of the leading neo-[[Aristotelianism|Aristotelian]] thinkers of his time.  He opposed such modern and contemporary developments as the "[[transcendental idealism|transcendental turn]]" and the "[[linguistic turn]]."  A staunch advocate of plain speaking and "[[Hoosier]]" common sense, in philosophy and elsewhere, he argued on behalf of [[philosophical realism|realist]] [[metaphysics]] and practical [[ethics]].<ref>Rocco Porecco and Ronald Duska, "Memorial Minutes: Henry Veatch 1911&ndash;1999," ''Proceedings and Addresses of the American Philosophical Association'', vol. 73, no. 2 (Nov/1999), pp. 31&ndash;2.</ref>\u000a\u000aVeatch's most widely read book was ''Rational Man: A Modern Interpretation of Aristotelian Ethics'' (1962) which explicitly offered a rationalist counterpoint to [[William Barrett (philosopher)|William Barrett's]] well-known study in [[existentialism|existential philosophy]], ''[[Irrational Man]]'' (1958).\u000a\u000a==Major works==\u000a*''Concerning the Ontological Status of Logical Forms'' (1948)\u000a*''Aristotelian and Mathematical Logic (1950)\u000a*''In Defense of the Syllogism'' (1950)\u000a*''Metaphysics and the Paradoxes'' (1952)\u000a*''[[Intentional Logic|Intentional Logic: A Logic Based on Philosophical Realism]]'' (1952)\u000a*''Realism and Nominalism Revisited'' (1954)\u000a*''Logic as a Human Instrument'' (1959, with Francis Parker)\u000a*''Rational Man: A Modern Interpretation of Aristotelian Ethics'' (1962)\u000a*''The Truths of Metaphysics'' (1964)\u000a*''Non-cognitivism in Ethics: A modest proposal for its diagnosis and cure'' (1966)\u000a*''Two Logics: the Conflict between Classical and Neo-Analytic Philosophy'' (1969)\u000a*''For an Ontology of Morals: A Critique of Contemporary Ethical Theory '' (1971)\u000a*''Aristotle: A Contemporary Appreciation'' (1974)\u000a*''Human Rights: Fact or Fancy'' (1985)\u000a*''Swimming Against the Current in Contemporary Philosophy'' (1990)\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a*[[American philosophy]]\u000a*[[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==Notes==\u000a<references/>\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Veatch, Henry Babcock}}\u000a[[Category:1911 births]]\u000a[[Category:1999 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American educators]]\u000a[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophy academics]]\u000a[[Category:Aristotelian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Christian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Indiana University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University staff]]\u000a[[Category:Moral philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Northwestern University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:People from Evansville, Indiana]]\u000a[[Category:Georgetown University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Presidents of the Metaphysical Society of America]]\u000a[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\u000a[[Category:American logicians]]
